          "body": "9:30-32 is the structural heart of the chapter and of Mark's second half. Jesus withdraws into Galilee, refuses publicity, and teaches the Twelve: *The Son of Man is to be delivered into the hands of men, and they will kill Him; and when He has been killed, He will rise three days later*. The verb *paradidomi* (delivered, handed over) is the same verb used of John the Baptist (1:14), of Judas (14:10-11), and of Pilate (15:1, 15) — the passion is a chain of human hand-offs that masks a divine handing-over (cf. Rom 8:32; Isa 53:6 LXX). The disciples *did not understand* and *were afraid to ask* (v. 32). Mark's repeated emphasis on disciple incomprehension throughout 8:31-10:45 is not literary embarrassment — it is the gospel's diagnosis. The cross is not naturally graspable; it must be revealed and submitted to."
