          "body": "The chapter closes (9:42-50) with the most severe judgment language in Mark's gospel. Causing a *mikros* (little one) to stumble warrants a fate worse than violent drowning (v. 42). The amputation sayings (vv. 43-47) are not commands to self-mutilate; they are hyperbolic indictments of any allegiance — hand, foot, eye — that competes with allegiance to Christ. Three times Jesus names Gehenna (vv. 43, 45, 47) and pairs it with Isaiah 66:24 (v. 48) — *their worm does not die, and the fire is not quenched*. The chapter's final words (vv. 49-50) reframe fire from threat to refinement: *everyone will be salted with fire*. The same fire that destroys the unrepentant purifies the disciple. Salt — preservative, distinctive, peace-making — is the chapter's closing metaphor for the cruciform community Jesus is forming. *Have salt in yourselves, and be at peace with one another* (v. 50) ties the entire chapter together: the disciples who argued about greatness (v. 34) must now live the salted life of those who follow the crucified Son of Man."
